The Marquesas Islands are fortunate to have a high concentration of phytoplankton around their islands, which is known as an "island effect."

The speaker then shares that they are an oceanographer who has studied this phenomenon using computer models and satellite data. Through their research, the speaker found that both physical processes (currents) and biological processes (nutrient inputs) contribute to the high levels of phytoplankton in the Marquesas Islands. They also discovered that iron-rich nutrients from the islands themselves are essential for boosting phytoplankton production.

The speaker concludes by saying that they hope their research will give people a new perspective on the Marquesas Islands and its unique ecosystem.

This is a transcript of a lecture or presentation on the topic of biomarkers and their application in diagnosing diseases, particularly intellectual disability. The speaker discusses how biomarkers can help detect specific molecules in the blood that indicate the presence or development of a disease.

The speaker starts by comparing the detection of rhinovirus (common cold) with the detection of high cholesterol levels in the blood, highlighting the importance of biomarkers in diagnosing diseases.

The speaker then turns to intellectual disability, noting that it is difficult to diagnose and that current methods rely on tests such as intelligence quotient (IQ) tests. The speaker mentions that genetic testing can be used to detect certain mutations, but these tests are expensive and do not provide information on whether the mutation is causing the disease.

The speaker then introduces their own research focus, which is on a specific type of intellectual disability called non-syndromic intellectual disability (NSID). NSID is characterized by significant cognitive impairment without any other physical or behavioral symptoms. The speaker notes that this type of intellectual disability is particularly challenging to diagnose and treat.

To address this challenge, the speaker's research focuses on identifying biomarkers in the blood that can detect NSID earlier and more accurately than current methods. The speaker mentions two key findings from their research:

1. They identified a specific gene mutation that causes NSID and then replicated this finding using Drosophila (fruit flies) as a model organism.
2. They discovered specific molecular fragments, called transfer RNA (tRNA) fragments, that accumulate in the blood of individuals with NSID.

The speaker concludes by noting that while detecting intellectual disability may not be as straightforward as detecting common cold or high cholesterol levels, biomarkers can still play an important role in improving diagnosis and treatment outcomes.

Here is the combined text:

Since ancient times, there has been a secret war that has already claimed millions of lives. I myself have lost some comrades, and perhaps you too. I am thinking in particular of the young foals who lived on the farm next to my parents' house when I was younger, and unfortunately did not survive. In this war, we have a common enemy - humans, animals, whether terrestrial or marine, insects, birds, and even plants. This common enemy is the parasitic worm. Parasitic worms are everywhere and come in all sizes. Some are microscopic and live in soil, and those are very good for the environment. On the other hand, others are very nasty and parasitize almost all living species on this planet. In humans, one person out of two is infested or has been infested. So look at your neighbor to your left, your neighbor to your right. If it's not you, it may be your neighbor who is infested. I can't take care of all the parasites that exist on this earth, so I will focus on the one that traumatized me as a child - the worm that affects horses and causes respiratory and digestive problems that can lead to animal death. We do have an arm against this worm - ivermectin. Ivermectin was commercialized in the 1980s, which means it's been around for 40 years. And that's where the problem is. Just like with antibiotics and bacteria, worms have developed resistances to this molecule. That's where I come in. The goal of my thesis is to understand how ivermectin works on this parasite, because we still don't know after 40 years, and to understand the mechanisms of resistance involved against this molecule to develop new strategies for fighting it. So we do have some leads. We know that ivermectin acts on the nervous system of the parasite, specifically on receptors. These receptors are composed of five subunits, like five fingers, and allow a nerve signal to pass or not depending on whether the receptor opens or closes. The worm has an idea - move, eat, reproduce. The idea passes through this receptor and leads to action - eating, moving, reproducing. Ivermectin, on the other hand, will bind to this receptor and prevent the worm from realizing its actions. So the worm is paralyzed and dies. But if the worm is resistant, ivermectin won't be able to bind to the receptor, and the worm will live freely in the horse. The goal of my thesis is already to identify these receptors and find the right subunit composition so that the receptor is functional, and then study the interactions between this receptor and ivermectin, the molecule used to treat this parasite. In a second stage, I will focus on the mutations of resistance that exist on this receptor to develop a new strategy and bypass the resistance. So you can count on me - I'll give it my all to save the foals.

Here is the transcript with English translation:

**Original text:**

En ce moment, sans vous en rendre compte, vous respirez de l'oxygène et expirez du dioxyde de carbone. Mais ce n'est pas exceptionnel, puisque la majorité des êtres vivants utilisent ce mode de respiration.

**Translation:**

Right now, without you realizing it, you're breathing in oxygen and exhaling carbon dioxide. But that's not unusual, since most living beings use this form of respiration.

Pendant mes travaux de thèse, je m'intéresse à de minuscules organismes marins capables de vivre temporairement sans oxygène dans le sédiment, ce sable qui tapisse le fond des mers et des océans. Mais qui sont ces incroyables micro-organismes ? Ce sont des foraminifères, comme Nonionella, caricaturé ici par Noni. Ils ressemblent à de petits coquillages, mais ce ne sont ni des animaux, ni des bactéries.

**Translation:**

During my thesis work, I'm studying tiny marine organisms that can temporarily survive without oxygen in the sediment, which covers the bottom of oceans and seas. But who are these incredible microorganisms? They're foraminifera, like Nonionella, caricatured here by Noni. They look like small shells, but they're neither animals nor bacteria.

L'objectif de la première partie de ma thèse est de comprendre la vie de Noni et son environnement chimique. Noni vit dans un fjord en Suède. Un fjord, c'est une cuvette d'eau de mer entre des montagnes et en hiver, le tapis roulant des courants marins n'a pas de nom. Il n'apporte pas suffisamment d'oxygène dans le fond de la cuvette.

**Translation:**

The objective of the first part of my thesis is to understand Noni's life and chemical environment. Noni lives in a fjord in Sweden. A fjord is a marine basin between mountains, and during winter, the rolling currents don't have a name. It doesn't bring enough oxygen to the bottom of the basin.

Ce manque d'oxygène est appelé hypoxie. Et ça, c'est une condition extrême pour la vie. Plusieurs solutions s'offrent alors pour les organismes. Soit ils meurent, soit ils s'enfuient, soit ils s'adaptent. Récemment, des collègues internationaux ont découvert que certains foraminifères, en absence d'oxygène, sont capables de respirer des nitrates et d'expirer de l'azote, comme Noni.

**Translation:**

This lack of oxygen is called hypoxia. And that's an extreme condition for life. Several solutions then offer themselves to organisms. Either they die, or they flee, or they adapt. Recently, international colleagues have discovered that certain foraminifera, in the absence of oxygen, are capable of respiring nitrates and exhaling nitrogen, like Noni.

C'est ce qu'on appelle la dénitrification. Alors là, vous vous dites, nitrate égale pollution ? Pollution, oui, mais pas que. Il ne faut pas oublier que les nitrates sont avant tout une molécule essentielle à la vie marine et à la vie végétale.

**Translation:**

That's what we call denitrification. So then you think, nitrate equals pollution? Pollution, yes, but not just that. We shouldn't forget that nitrates are primarily an essential molecule for marine life and plant life.

Imaginez-vous une campagne océanographique, en Suède en hiver. Alors déjà, il fait nuit, il fait froid, et en plus, ça sent l'oeuf pourri à cause des sulfures.

**Translation:**

Imagine an oceanographic campaign in Sweden during winter. Already it's night, it's cold, and to boot, it smells like rotten eggs due to the sulfides.

Bonjour l'ambiance.

Dans le premier article scientifique que je suis en train d'écrire, j'ai réussi à quantifier la respiration de Noni, et à cartographier son environnement chimique en deux dimensions. Montrant que Noni, ainsi que ses milliers de frères et sœurs, sont capables de consommer la totalité des nitrates contenus dans le sédiment du fjord.

**Translation:**

Hello ambiance.

In the first scientific article I'm writing, I've managed to quantify Noni's respiration and map its chemical environment in two dimensions. Showing that Noni, along with thousands of its siblings, is capable of consuming all the nitrates present in the sediment of the fjord.

Faisant ainsi de Noni une espèce bio-indicatrice d'un milieu riche en nitrates et faible en oxygène. Super.

**Translation:**

Making Noni a biological indicator species for an environment rich in nitrates and low in oxygen. Great.

Mais à quoi ça sert de savoir ça, finalement ? Eh bien, vous devez savoir que de nos jours, les océans sont menacés par une hypoxie croissante due aux changements climatiques et aux impacts anthropiques.

**Translation:**

But what does it matter to know this, finally? Well, you should know that today's oceans are threatened by a growing hypoxia due to climate change and human impacts.

Le problème, c'est que le modèle plateforme a déjà lutté. Désormais, ce modèle est sous forme pyramidale. Au sommet, on a une plateforme détentrice de l'autorité. En dessous, on a des prestataires aux frais, par exemple des livreurs, qui auraient obtenu une sorte de promotion et qui auraient obtenu une sorte de promotion.

Et eux aussi sont détenteurs d'autorité. Au troisième étage de cette pyramide, on retrouve des sociétés de location de matériel qui également sont détentrices d'autorité. Et tout en bas, on a un prestataire aux frais final qui se voit apposer l'autorité des trois premiers étages de la pyramide.

Alors, ce prestataire aux frais final est-ce qu'il est subordonné ? Eh bien non, parce que l'éparpillement des pouvoirs entre les mains des trois premiers étages de la pyramide empêche la reprise de la plateforme. Et il a aussi la reconnaissance d'une subordination juridique formelle.

Alors, qu'est-ce qu'on fait ? Eh bien, on va aller chercher dans notre corpus juridique un droit qui aurait pu acconnaître de ses relations de contrôle, de domination et de pouvoir. Et il n'en est qu'un, c'est le droit de la concurrence.

Et mon idée, c'est de prendre le droit de la concurrence et d'insérer une partie vers le droit du travail. L'objectif final, c'est quoi ? C'est d'offrir une protection à ce travailleur pas vraiment indépendant. Et leur ouvrir droit à la protection du droit du travail.

Savez-vous comment nourrir 10 milliards de personnes en 2050 ? Le manque des ressources telles que l'eau et les sols rend difficile la réponse à cette question. D'autant plus que le système alimentaire actuel, lui-même basé sur l'utilisation intensive de ces ressources-là, s'avère fragile et ne pourra donc tenir devant le risque d'insécurité alimentaire qui s'annonce d'ici quelques décennies seulement.

Et si les insectes étaient la solution ? En entendant le mot insecte, certains d'entre vous penseraient à la pollinisation des abeilles, aux piqûres de guêpes ou encore aux champs des criquets qui leur tenaient compagnie lors des belles soirées d'été. Alors moi, quand j'entends ce terme, je pense réellement à notre future alimentation.

Et oui, vous ne le savez peut-être pas, mais les insectes sont parmi les animaux les plus abondants et les plus nutritifs de la planète. Ils sont cultivés à grande échelle et peuvent être une vraie alternative alimentaire durable pour le consommateur de demain. La composition des insectes en protéines, vitamines et minéraux leur procure une valeur nutritionnelle qui correspond au double de la valeur nutritionnelle des aliments habituels.

De plus, ils émettent de 10 à 100 fois moins de déchets et de gaz. Et ils ne sont plus aussi efficaces à effet de serre que les animaux vertébrés. Et leur faible concentration en glucides permet de les préconiser pour des régimes ou carrément pour des programmes médicaux.

Alors en s'inspirant des études déjà réalisées sur une population d'adultes occidentaux, ayant déjà une perception assez négative de cette pratique, ma recherche se focalise sur les enfants. Vous allez me dire pourquoi ? Eh bien tout simplement. Parce que les enfants, de par leur nature, ils conçoivent le monde différemment des adultes.

Par ailleurs, ils sont de forts diffuseurs d'innovation au sein du foyer. Vous l'aurez donc compris, l'objectif de ma thèse est de comprendre la perception des enfants à l'égard de cette pratique afin d'anticiper et d'accompagner leurs évolutions comportementales.

Pour ce faire, je mène un ensemble d'entretiens avec des enfants de 6 à 12 ans. Et après les avoir transcrits, ces entretiens me permettront par la suite de détecter les facteurs sensoriels, psychologiques et culturels derrière leurs freins et leurs motivations.

Alors si je fais tout ça et que je viens aujourd'hui pour vous le raconter, c'est juste pour vous dire que pour une planète saine et durable, le moindre petit geste compte. Et si cette image vous paraît aujourd'hui bizarre, d'ici quelques années... Elle vous paraîtra tout à fait normale.

In my laboratory, we ask a simple question that you may have already asked yourself: how do babies make themselves? Beyond the evasive answers parents give their children, we really want to know how, from a fertilized egg cell, one arrives at entire organisms like you and me. What particularly interests me during embryonic development is neurons, cells that transmit information. How do they position themselves in the right place in the organism and connect correctly with each other to form functional circuits? These questions have already been well studied from a chemical perspective, with the discovery of molecules that guide neurons, but the novelty of my project is to look at the role of mechanical forces in setting up neural circuits. To do this, I use the zebrafish model, as you can see here on the left, with images taken either from the front or side. These images were taken about a day after spawning and by zooming in on the head of the embryo with a microscope, like the image at center, we can see the developing brain with eyes forming on either side and above, the future nostrils of the fish. In the nose of the zebrafish, neurons migrate away from the surface of the brain, while extending behind them a long arm, the axon, which allows them to connect with cells in the brain. This is the image we can see on the right. Neurons, like other cells, have intrinsic mechanisms that allow them to migrate and advance in their environment. In the case of nasal neurons, surprise, even when these intrinsic mechanisms don't work, neurons move forward and extend their axon to connect with the brain. It's a bit like watching a car on a flat terrain, whose engine is broken but which still moves forward. We can then think of two hypotheses: either there are people with brain problems or there are people pushing the car or pulling it. It's the same thing for nasal neurons. We think that these cells from the eye, located below, pull the nasal neurons to the side, leading to the extension of their axon and allowing them to connect with the brain. To verify this idea, I looked at embryos with a genetic mutation that don't form an eye. I saw that on these embryos, the nasal neurons don't move forward. These results come to confirm our hypothesis, according to which nasal neurons are identical, and therefore, they don't function correctly. This is a method by which eye cells pull nasal neurons, showing that there's not just chemistry involved during development but also mechanical forces. Beyond the nose of the zebrafish, understanding the role of mechanical forces in development will shed new light on diseases of the nervous system. So may the force be with your neurons!

"It's not easy to pilot an airplane, that's why since the early days of aviation, we've created flight simulators. So, you have to imagine a cockpit with screens that make you believe you're on the runway, ready to take off. But, if you only learn from this visual information and try to fly a plane in real conditions, you'll quickly realize there's still much to learn. It's because you lack essential vestibular information during your training. Vestibular information comes from an organ located inside your inner ear, which gives you all the information about your body position in space. That's why flight simulators can move in every direction to recreate real conditions. Your brain needs a maximum of information to learn, and these come from different sensory organs in your body. Here, it's the eyes and vestibular system. The question I ask myself is: how does the brain process this information? Scientists have already asked themselves this question, but they only looked at a few neurons. But multi-sensory processes involve different regions of the brain, and therefore thousands of neurons. It's like trying to study Paris traffic by looking at just one car. But if you can follow all the cars at once, you'll quickly get the overall network, its dynamics, and interactions between all these cars. And that's exactly what I want to do. Measure the activity of each neuron in the brain simultaneously. And the only vertebrate that will be most important is the brain. The traffic that allows me to experience this today is the zebrafish larva. Because it's completely transparent and its brain measures less than a millimeter. It's perfect for placing under a microscope and looking at its brain all at once.

The first step of my thesis was to build a flight simulator for a zebrafish larva. The idea is exactly the same, except that the larvae are placed in a small aquarium and fixed with agarose gel, like a pilot attached to his seat. I also added a screen around the larva to simulate a visual environment.

The second step of my thesis was to add an option. I miniaturized an embedded microscope that allows me to photograph different layers of the brain. Thus, I get a 3D image of the brain with a 4th dimension, time, which gives me access to the dynamics of neurons. Thanks to this experience, I was able to measure the neural dynamics for the first time when the larva is moved left or right. My goal is to complete this map with the neural dynamics when there is a visual environment around the larvae. This will allow me to find out which neurons are active in both cases and understand how this brain composed of about 100,000 neurons processes sensory information."
